{"title":"Lads on (Grand) Tour: The 8 British riders at the Vuelta a España 2023","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/british-riders-vuelta-espana","date":1692981399000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/british-riders-vuelta-espana\">Lads on (Grand) Tour: The 8 British riders at the Vuelta a España 2023</a></p>\n\n<p>The 2023 <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/vuelta-a-espana\" target=\"_blank\">Vuelta a España</a> starts in Barcelona on Saturday 26th August with <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/vuelta-a-espana-route-race-reports-tv-guide-and-all-you-need-to-know\" target=\"_blank\">an insanely hard route</a> that includes climbs of the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/geraint-thomas\" target=\"_blank\">Col du Tourmalet</a> and <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-climbs-alto-de-l-angliru\" target=\"_blank\">Alto de l’Angliru</a> and features one of the strongest start lists in any race this season.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Headlined by Tour de France winner <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/jonas-vingegaard\" target=\"_blank\">Jonas Vingegaard</a>, his teammate, Giro winner and three-time Vuelta winner <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/primoz-roglic\" target=\"_blank\">Primož Roglič</a>, defending champion <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/remco-evenepoel\" target=\"_blank\">Remco Evenepoel</a> and Spain’s next great Grand Tour rider Juan Ayuso, there’s a lot of attention on the favourites for the general classification, however look beyond the big names and there’s an endless list of strong veterans and promising young talent to pack the next three weeks with entertaining racing.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Among them are eight British riders looking to make their mark in the final Grand Tour of the year. For many it’ll be their first three-week race, for others it’s another chance to add to their legacy.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>So, who are they, what are their roles and what are their chances of winning something? Let’s find out.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-espana-prize-money\">How much is the 2023 Vuelta a España prize money?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-espana-red-jersey\">The Vuelta a España leader’s red jersey: Everything you need to know</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-a-espana-favourites\">Who are the favourites for the 2023 Vuelta a España?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/how-watch-vuelta-espana\">How to watch and live stream the Vuelta a España 2023</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/vuelta-a-espana-route-race-reports-tv-guide-and-all-you-need-to-know\">Vuelta a España 2023: Stage-by-stage preview and everything we know so far</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Geraint Thomas, Ineos Grenadiers</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-970x647.jpeg\" alt=\"two cyclists mid-race, front in red and blue kit with white-framed sunglasses and back one in white with black shorts and a white helmet\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-970x646.jpeg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-300x200.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-1536x1024.jpeg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-2048x1366.jpeg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-750x500.jpeg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-1140x760.jpeg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-465x310.jpeg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-620x413.jpeg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/05/geraint-thomas-ineos-grenadiers-giro-ditalia-2023-350x233.jpeg 350w\" /><figcaption>Ineos Grenadiers</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The biggest name on the list is of course <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/geraint-thomas\" target=\"_blank\">Geraint Thomas</a>. The former Tour de France winner came within a whisker of winning the Giro d’Italia earlier in the year, just losing the pink jersey on the final mountain time-trial to Roglič. He’ll be Ineos Grenadiers’ GC man once again and has a strong team to support him, but will it be enough to win the Vuelta’s red jersey? It’s unlikely but don’t count him out. It’s only his second time at the race, so it’s almost unknown territory and he could benefit from the other contenders looking at each other.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>James Knox, Soudal-QuickStep</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"cyclist looks sad\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-james-knox-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Tim de Waele/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>This will be James Knox’s third Vuelta and arguably his most important as he’ll be one of Evenepoel’s most important mountain domestiques in the battle against an almighty Jumbo-Visma team. A more than capable climber, Knox finished 11th overall on his first Vuelta appearance in 2019 and bagged second in the National Championships road race earlier in the year. Because of Soudal-QuickStep’s commitment to Evenepoel, Knox should get plenty of TV time but won’t get the chance to fight for his own glory.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Sean Flynn, DSM-Firmenich</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"647\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-647x970.jpg\" alt=\"cyclist on podium smiling\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-647x970.jpg 647w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-200x300.jpg 200w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-750x1125.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-1140x1710.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-sean-flynn-scaled.jpg 1706w\" /><figcaption>Gongora/NurPhoto via Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The first of three young Brits on DSM-Firmenich’s Vuelta squad is Sean Flynn. It’s the Scot’s first season with the team and first in the WorldTour having signed from Swiss outfit Tudor in the off-season. 23-year-old Flynn has a multi-discipline background, coming into the sport through mountain biking and winning the Junior Cyclocross National Championship in 2018, but is now focussed on the road with DSM. Built for the Classics, Flynn will either be looking to get into breakaway on the less hilly stages or helping the team’s sprinter Alberto Dainese.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Oscar Onley, DSM-Firmenich</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"674\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-970x674.jpg\" alt=\"three cyclists on podium\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-970x674.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-300x208.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-768x534.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-1536x1067.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-2048x1423.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-750x521.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-oscar-onley-cro-race-2022-1140x792.jpg 1140w\" /><figcaption>Marko Lukunic/Pixsell/MB Media/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>20-year-old Oscar Onley is in his first pro season and has already signed a contract at DSM-Firmenich until 2027, which says it all. In 2022 he finished third on general classification at Cro Race behind Matej Mohorič and Jonas Vingegaard and you can expect there’ll be a lot more podiums to come. Team leader Romain Bardet is normally left to fend for himself so expect Onley to get himself into several breakaways on hard stages – of which there are plenty – and don’t be surprised if he comes away with a stage win. </p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Max Poole, DSM-Firmenich</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"cyclist in white on a podium\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-max-poole-dauphine-2023-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Dario Belingheri/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Just like Onley, Max Poole is a 20-year-old neo-pro climbing specialist who has already signed with the team until 2027. Poole, from Scunthorpe, has had several strong performances this season including fourth overall at the Tour de Romandie. Expect to see him up there on the hardest stages whether that be in the breakaway or sticking with the main favourites and again a stage win could be on the cards.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Sam Watson, Groupama-FDJ</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"two cyclists in blue\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-lewis-askey-sam-watson-vuelta-2023-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Lewis Askey (left) and Sam Watson (right)</figcaption><figcaption>Gongora/NurPhoto via Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The other team who have brought through a lot of young British talent recently in Grouapama-FDJ and they have two Brits on their team here, the first of whom is Sam Watson. A true talent for the Classics, Watson is an incredibly strong rider with several high-placed finishes already in his young career included three top seven finishes at last year’s Tour of Britain, second at the 2022 National Championships – and fifth this year – and fifth at the 2022 Tro Bro Léon. With the youth of his team he’ll likely be given an opportunity or two in breakaways, he might also be deployed to help Lenny Martinez should he find himself high up on GC.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Lewis Askey, Groupama-FDJ</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Lewis Askey is another rider building himself into a fine Classics specialist with his most notable result 25th at Paris-Roubaix, in what was essentially the third group on the road that was came in from 15th place with several big names. He’ll have a similar role to Watson in that he’ll likely be allowed to find his own opportunities but he could also become a valuable domestique if required.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Hugh Carthy, EF Education-EasyPost</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"646\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-970x646.jpg\" alt=\"cyclist in pink celebrating\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-768x511.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-1536x1022.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-2048x1363.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-750x499.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-1140x759.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/GettyImages-hugh-carthy-angliru-2020-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>MIGUEL RIOPA/AFP via Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Hugh Carthy is heading up the EF Education-EasyPost in the final Grand Tour of a contract year, and with no wins since 2021, it is vital he shows something here. Carthy is no stranger to this race however, and this will be his sixth Vuelta. He spent two years with Spanish team Caja Rural-Seguros RGA and the biggest win of his career came here in 2020 on the Alto de l’Angliru of all places. And guess what climb is making its first appearance since 2020 this year? Bring it home.</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/british-riders-vuelta-espana\">Lads on (Grand) Tour: The 8 British riders at the Vuelta a España 2023</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"Robyn Davidson &#124; Editorial Assistant","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"a869fc63edf71600a6ad472ce1331347c33049225cd537465acdc1c6db4fbff8","category":"Cycling"}